import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Toca Boca — Pablo Anttila">
  <main>
    <nav aria-label="breadcrumb">
      <a href="/work">← All work</a>
    </nav>

    <header>
      <small>2020–2021</small>
      <h1>Toca Boca</h1>
      <p>Player Identity System</p>
    </header>

    <figure>
      <p>[Project screenshot]</p>
    </figure>

    <article>
      <h2>What</h2>
      <p>A login and friend system for <strong>Toca Life World</strong>, one of the most downloaded kids' apps in the world. The system enables multiplayer features in Toca Boca's suite of games while keeping children safe.</p>

      <h2>My role</h2>
      <p>Frontend lead on a small team — three developers and a PM. I owned the React/TypeScript web interface and drove the UX design process.</p>

      <h2>The challenge</h2>
      <p>Building authentication flows for kids aged 7–12, with parental controls, friend codes, and zero tolerance for dark patterns. This is a space full of bad actors — privacy-first design wasn't optional.</p>

      <h2>What I built</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Parent dashboard (web)</strong> — React + TypeScript interface for account management</li>
        <li><strong>Friend code system</strong> — Kid-safe way to connect with friends without exposing personal data</li>
        <li><strong>Email verification flows</strong> — For parental consent (COPPA compliance)</li>
        <li><strong>Component library</strong> — Shared UI kit for the team</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Stack</h2>
      <p>
        {['React', 'TypeScript', 'NestJS', 'AWS', 'Docker', 'Jest', 'Cypress'].map(tech => (
          <code>{tech}</code>
        ))}
      </p>

      <h2>The hard part</h2>
      <p>Designing "fun" authentication for kids without manipulating them. Every screen had legal review. Every copy choice mattered. We couldn't use the usual engagement tricks — no streaks, no FOMO, no pressure.</p>
      <p>The result was slower but more honest. Kids could connect with friends using simple codes. Parents had real visibility and control. The system passed regulatory review in multiple jurisdictions.</p>

      <h2>Outcome</h2>
      <p>[Pablo: Add metrics if you have them — users, adoption rate, anything quantifiable. Even "shipped to X million users" works.]</p>
    </article>

    <nav>
